00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:38.960
What's your opinion
on the work that you

00:29:38.960 --> 00:29:43.550
see DeepMind doing in terms of
changing games from-- rather

00:29:43.550 --> 00:29:46.160
far more to the scale element
and kind of the way computers

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:47.122
are working on games?

00:29:47.122 --> 00:29:48.830
ADAM KUCHARSKI: I
think one of the things

00:29:48.830 --> 00:29:49.910
with Go that stands
out, and it's

00:29:49.910 --> 00:29:51.520
similar with poker,
is just the speed

00:29:51.520 --> 00:29:53.269
at which these
developments are happening.

00:29:53.269 --> 00:29:54.820
So I think Go for
a lot of people

00:29:54.820 --> 00:29:57.020
was safe from computers
for a few more years

00:29:57.020 --> 00:29:59.900
and, similarly, with a lot
of the more complex forms

00:29:59.900 --> 00:30:00.400
of poker.

00:30:00.400 --> 00:30:02.080
So no-limit, hold 'em,
and these kind of things.

00:30:02.080 --> 00:30:04.050
I think people had this
idea that humans would

00:30:04.050 --> 00:30:05.190
be dominant for a lot longer.

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:07.250
So I think that's quite
interesting in the time scale.

00:30:07.250 --> 00:30:09.083
Also with Go, just the
way it's tackling it,

00:30:09.083 --> 00:30:10.920
because obviously it's
a game that you can't

00:30:10.920 --> 00:30:12.450
find this optimal solution.

00:30:12.450 --> 00:30:15.670
So from what I
understand, it's much more

00:30:15.670 --> 00:30:17.880
about understanding
the shape of the board.

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:20.537
So adopting almost
more human approaches

00:30:20.537 --> 00:30:23.120
to learn these games rather than
simply crunching the numbers,

00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:24.480
as you might do for
a very simple game.

00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:26.520
So I think that's quite
interesting of having

00:30:26.520 --> 00:30:28.145
to reproduce human
learning techniques.

00:30:28.145 --> 00:30:30.930
And actually, for poker,
a lot of the algorithms

00:30:30.930 --> 00:30:32.550
they use to try
and solve these are

00:30:32.550 --> 00:30:33.900
based on regret minimizations.

00:30:33.900 --> 00:30:37.580
So they have a kind of regret
function within their learning

00:30:37.580 --> 00:30:38.190
component.

00:30:38.190 --> 00:30:41.300
So I think that's actually quite
interesting, just coming out

00:30:41.300 --> 00:30:43.810
as a side issue, of what the
efficient ways of learning

00:30:43.810 --> 00:30:46.409
these kind of games are.

