came out of games and
gambling we use in our work.

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:06.900
So an obvious example is things
like Monte Carlo simulations,

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:10.240
that generally if you try
to infer what disease does,

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:13.130
you need some way of
combining a simulation

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:15.279
process with inference of data.

00:31:15.279 --> 00:31:17.070
And so actually, in
this kind of situation,

00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:20.350
it's much more efficient to
just do lots of simulations

00:31:20.350 --> 00:31:22.757
and then kind of refine
them to what the data is.

00:31:22.757 --> 00:31:24.590
But there's a number
of other ideas as well.

00:31:24.590 --> 00:31:26.670
So in some situations,
people using game theory.

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:29.602
Again, these kind of strategies
that came out of betting to

00:31:29.602 --> 00:31:31.810
understand how different
countries may be interacting

00:31:31.810 --> 00:31:33.780
to make vaccine decisions.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:35.530
Because in many
situations, you have

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.100
almost like a tragedy of
the commons, from something

00:31:38.100 --> 00:31:41.220
where you've potentially got a
vaccine that has a side effect

00:31:41.220 --> 00:31:42.620
or has a problem.

00:31:42.620 --> 00:31:44.070
From an individual
point of view,

00:31:44.070 --> 00:31:45.660
your priorities and
your risk profile

00:31:45.660 --> 00:31:48.074
is very different to
what a population does.

00:31:48.074 --> 00:31:50.240
So if you have a whole
population making a decision,

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:52.250
you might have some
effective herd immunity.

00:31:52.250 --> 00:31:55.000
But if enough
individuals ignore that,

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:56.740
you can end up with
a different outcome.

00:31:56.740 --> 00:31:58.590
So it's the push and
pull between what's

00:31:58.590 --> 00:32:00.715
good for a population and
what's good at individual

00:32:00.715 --> 00:32:02.750
and how those things interact.

00:32:02.750 --> 00:32:05.160
So I think that's where a
lot of the ideas come into.

00:32:05.160 --> 00:32:07.020
I think it's also just
good sometimes when

00:32:07.020 --> 00:32:08.811
you're working with
these ideas day in, day

00:32:08.811 --> 00:32:11.220
out, to understand
where they come from.

00:32:11.220 --> 00:32:14.040
And I think as well just the
fact that these kind of games

00:32:14.040 --> 00:32:16.050
are very nice situations.

00:32:16.050 --> 00:32:19.430
If you work in disease
data, it's pretty murky.

00:32:19.430 --> 00:32:21.590
There's a lot of unknowns,
a lot of uncertainty,

00:32:21.590 --> 00:32:25.000
whereas for something like a
simplified version of poker,

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:27.964
it's a sort of well-defined
problem to work on.

00:32:27.964 --> 00:32:29.380
So I think you do
in any industry,

00:32:29.380 --> 00:32:31.000
you work on kind of
cartoon problems,

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:33.070
because they're
simple to analyze.

00:32:33.070 --> 00:32:34.780
I think it's just
interesting to see

00:32:34.780 --> 00:32:37.399
how the history has developed
in these kind of things.

00:32:37.399 --> 00:32:39.440
AUDIENCE: The disease
data, I'm quite interested.

00:32:39.440 --> 00:32:43.270
And we hear a lot about
immunization-- sorry,

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.390
the way that antibiotics
will affect us

00:32:45.390 --> 00:32:48.200
on a global population and
that we might not globally

00:32:48.200 --> 00:32:51.410
be prepared for outbreak
of a pandemic or similar.

00:32:51.410 --> 00:32:54.199
And that often feels like
it's a governmental problem--

00:32:54.199 --> 00:32:56.490
governments communicating
with each other and so forth.

00:32:56.490 --> 00:32:58.370
So as a mathematician,
as a scientist,

00:32:58.370 --> 00:33:02.220
how do you look to
communicate your findings

00:33:02.220 --> 00:33:04.440
onto a kind of political
and to a human level

00:33:04.440 --> 00:33:09.370
and try to impact the system
that is often quite messy?

00:33:09.370 --> 00:33:11.490
ADAM KUCHARSKI: That's
a good question.

00:33:11.490 --> 00:33:13.759
Doing Ebola, we did
quite a lot of work

00:33:13.759 --> 00:33:14.800
with government agencies.

00:33:14.800 --> 00:33:17.258
And I think one of the things
they say is it's better to be

00:33:17.258 --> 00:33:19.520
80% right today than 90%
right in two years' time.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:21.780
And it's really kind of
working on-- there's never

00:33:21.780 --> 00:33:23.979
a single piece of research
that defines a policy.

00:33:23.979 --> 00:33:25.520
It's always that
kind of aggregation.

00:33:25.520 --> 00:33:27.770
But I think there's
often situations

00:33:27.770 --> 00:33:29.410
that there's a lot of options.

00:33:29.410 --> 00:33:31.240
It's not clear what's
even reasonable.

00:33:31.240 --> 00:33:33.310
I think modeling and a
mathematical approach

00:33:33.310 --> 00:33:35.643
is a good way of essentially
taking things off the table

00:33:35.643 --> 00:33:37.710
and refining it down.

00:33:37.710 --> 00:33:40.356
I think, especially doing these
kind of real-time outbreaks,

00:33:40.356 --> 00:33:41.480
the Zika's another example.

00:33:41.480 --> 00:33:43.410
There's a huge amount
of uncertainty.

00:33:43.410 --> 00:33:45.915
And ideally, you'll get in and
do all kind of field studies

00:33:45.915 --> 00:33:47.040
and do everything properly.

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:49.970
But in the absence of that,
we need to make decisions now.

00:33:49.970 --> 00:33:51.420
I think these kind
of analysis are

00:33:51.420 --> 00:33:52.711
quite a useful way of doing it.

00:33:52.711 --> 00:33:55.290
I think policymakers
appreciate having things

00:33:55.290 --> 00:33:58.060
there very quickly as an
evidence base to make decisions

00:33:58.060 --> 00:33:59.730
on.

00:33:59.730 --> 00:34:02.170
AUDIENCE: I was just thinking
about your [INAUDIBLE] a bit

00:34:02.170 --> 00:34:05.692
like roulette moving from
more into a skill mode

00:34:05.692 --> 00:34:06.400
than a luck mode.

00:34:06.400 --> 00:34:09.090
Do you think the insurance
industry is actually

00:34:09.090 --> 00:34:10.590
going to be-- because
at the moment,

00:34:10.590 --> 00:34:12.290
it's just down on
this huge population,

00:34:12.290 --> 00:34:14.040
and you're roughly
going to die or roughly

00:34:14.040 --> 00:34:15.530
going to have a car crash.

00:34:15.530 --> 00:34:18.830
But actually, as you have
increasing levels of data

00:34:18.830 --> 00:34:22.050
about everything you do in a
car or every bit of genetics,

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:24.459
then it becomes
calculable potentially.

00:34:24.459 --> 00:34:27.205
Do you see that shift in
the insurance industry?

00:34:27.205 --> 00:34:28.080
ADAM KUCHARSKI: Yeah.

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:29.330
I mean, it's already happening.

00:34:29.330 --> 00:34:30.830
I don't know the
details, but I know

00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:33.350
there's been a few test
cases in recent years of that

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:35.510
trying to refine it
into certain parts.

00:34:35.510 --> 00:34:38.120
So the split between males
and females, for example.

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:40.920
And I think there's
been some legal disputes

00:34:40.920 --> 00:34:42.690
as to whether you
can actually do that.

00:34:42.690 --> 00:34:43.440
And you're right.

00:34:43.440 --> 00:34:45.761
It makes sense if you had
that large set of data,

00:34:45.761 --> 00:34:47.600
because you can really
refine the risk based

00:34:47.600 --> 00:34:48.725
on a particular individual.

00:34:48.725 --> 00:34:51.710
But there's that kind of
conflict between people

00:34:51.710 --> 00:34:53.944
wanting a uniform policy.

00:34:53.944 --> 00:34:55.860
So again, that's the
kind of interesting thing

00:34:55.860 --> 00:34:59.120
of where what the model says
is best conflicts with what's

00:34:59.120 --> 00:35:00.590
actually acceptable.

00:35:00.590 --> 00:35:03.120
AUDIENCE: So if
you've got an opponent

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:05.430
that you know is playing
a perfect strategy,

00:35:05.430 --> 00:35:07.580
is there any way to use
that information to game

00:35:07.580 --> 00:35:09.500
that opponent?

00:35:09.500 --> 00:35:12.161
And are there some games
which are, because of this,

00:35:12.161 --> 00:35:12.660
intractable?

00:35:15.520 --> 00:35:18.420
ADAM KUCHARSKI: So if you're
playing a perfect opponent,

00:35:18.420 --> 00:35:21.330
then I suppose by the
definition of that strategy,

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:24.660
your best response is to play
an equilibrium strategy as well.

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:25.790
One of the things that's
interesting, actually,

00:35:25.790 --> 00:35:27.915
talking to people who are
working these poker games

00:35:27.915 --> 00:35:29.651
is, in two-player
situations, it's

00:35:29.651 --> 00:35:32.150
pretty obvious that, if they're
playing an optimal strategy,

00:35:32.150 --> 00:35:33.740
you need to do the same.

00:35:33.740 --> 00:35:36.190
But the definition of an
[INAUDIBLE] equilibrium

00:35:36.190 --> 00:35:37.850
is on unilateral behavior.

00:35:37.850 --> 00:35:41.350
So it's no player has anything
to gain by individually

00:35:41.350 --> 00:35:42.370
changing that strategy.

00:35:42.370 --> 00:35:43.869
But when you have
multiplayer games,

00:35:43.869 --> 00:35:47.346
you have the potential for
collaboration and coalitions.

00:35:47.346 --> 00:35:49.970
And actually, some of the people
working on poker, particularly

00:35:49.970 --> 00:35:53.311
on the versions of the
game that are intractable,

00:35:53.311 --> 00:35:55.560
have found that you can have
these kind of equilibrium

00:35:55.560 --> 00:35:56.060
strategies.

00:35:56.060 --> 00:35:57.639
And when people
put them together,

00:35:57.639 --> 00:35:59.680
potentially two players
could gang up on a third.

00:35:59.680 --> 00:36:01.770
And the third can't do
anything about that.

00:36:01.770 --> 00:36:03.890
So in that situation,
where they all

00:36:03.890 --> 00:36:05.640
are playing pretty
good strategies but not

00:36:05.640 --> 00:36:07.139
perfect ones, it
doesn't necessarily

00:36:07.139 --> 00:36:09.530
make sense for that person
who's being picked on

00:36:09.530 --> 00:36:11.200
to rely on that as a defense.

00:36:11.200 --> 00:36:13.290
And it might make
sense to look for flaws

00:36:13.290 --> 00:36:14.564
in what they're doing instead.

00:36:14.564 --> 00:36:15.980
So I think there's
just a lot more

00:36:15.980 --> 00:36:17.310
to be seen for when you
have these multiplayer

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:20.360
games, that it's not so clear
that these kind of equilibrium

00:36:20.360 --> 00:36:21.470
strategies are useful.

00:36:21.470 --> 00:36:22.826
Hopefully that answered your--

00:36:22.826 --> 00:36:24.650
AUDIENCE: It did, thanks.

00:36:24.650 --> 00:36:26.330
AUDIENCE: I'm very
curious as to what

00:36:26.330 --> 00:36:27.760
brought you down that path.

00:36:27.760 --> 00:36:30.206
Why did you write this book?

00:36:30.206 --> 00:36:32.330
ADAM KUCHARSKI: So I've
said, these kind of stories

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:34.280
have always been hovering
in the background for me.

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:36.071
And it was actually,
it was during my PhD--

00:36:36.071 --> 00:36:37.160
so I did PhD in maths.

00:36:37.160 --> 00:36:40.162
And we'd often get emails from
usually the standard crowd,

00:36:40.162 --> 00:36:41.870
just tons of investment
banks, generally.

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:44.410
But you'd often get a few
different ones appearing.

00:36:44.410 --> 00:36:46.800
And it was actually
firms who are essentially

00:36:46.800 --> 00:36:52.390
betting hedge funds got in touch
about possible recruitment.

00:36:52.390 --> 00:36:54.740
And for me, that was
something that I just

00:36:54.740 --> 00:36:56.880
wasn't aware of as an
industry that had developed.

00:36:56.880 --> 00:36:58.671
And actually, as you
start to look into it,

00:36:58.671 --> 00:37:00.360
it was only in the
last decade or two

00:37:00.360 --> 00:37:03.140
that in the UK on, say,
football that people

00:37:03.140 --> 00:37:04.850
have been able to
make consistently

00:37:04.850 --> 00:37:08.147
good enough predictions to make
that a viable business model.

00:37:08.147 --> 00:37:09.480
And that kind of started for me.

00:37:09.480 --> 00:37:10.370
That was quite interesting.

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:11.000
That was something
I was completely

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:12.240
unaware of as an industry.

00:37:12.240 --> 00:37:14.448
And then when you start to
dig down into the history,

00:37:14.448 --> 00:37:16.020
you realize that
not only there are

00:37:16.020 --> 00:37:18.395
a lot of other people doing
these things that potentially

00:37:18.395 --> 00:37:19.590
aren't reported a lot.

00:37:19.590 --> 00:37:22.252
Actually, you've got a lot
of quite major developments

00:37:22.252 --> 00:37:23.960
in science that-- I
don't know about you,

00:37:23.960 --> 00:37:25.430
but I was just
completely unaware

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:27.750
that a lot of these ideas
had originated with games

00:37:27.750 --> 00:37:29.402
like roulette and gambling.

00:37:29.402 --> 00:37:31.610
I thought it would just be
really interesting to have

00:37:31.610 --> 00:37:34.450
a book that explores not only
the history but also some

00:37:34.450 --> 00:37:36.966
of the modern efforts and,
again, with some developments

00:37:36.966 --> 00:37:37.465
in AI.

00:37:37.465 --> 00:37:39.810
I think that's coming
on frustratingly almost

00:37:39.810 --> 00:37:42.196
when you write a book, that
it's coming on so quickly,

00:37:42.196 --> 00:37:43.320
because it kind of updates.

00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:46.224
But I think that's
fascinating looking at what's

00:37:46.224 --> 00:37:47.390
happening in the modern day.

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:49.410
And it's just the
fundamental question of,

00:37:49.410 --> 00:37:51.950
if you're going to put money
on the line, what evidence

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:52.910
do you need to make a decision?

00:37:52.910 --> 00:37:55.030
And it's the same of whether
you're deploying a vaccine

00:37:55.030 --> 00:37:56.260
or whether you're making
a business choice.

00:37:56.260 --> 00:37:59.219
It's what evidence convinces you
that that risk is worth taking.

00:37:59.219 --> 00:38:01.260
I think gambling is a
really interesting industry

00:38:01.260 --> 00:38:04.450
to look at in that context.

00:38:04.450 --> 00:38:06.310
AUDIENCE: So we work
at Google, and we love

00:38:06.310 --> 00:38:07.670
data sets and big data sets.

00:38:07.670 --> 00:38:09.270
We had a speaker
recently who spoke

00:38:09.270 --> 00:38:12.590
of understanding whale
noises and that it's

00:38:12.590 --> 00:38:15.100
a problem where, if we
had a larger data set,

00:38:15.100 --> 00:38:17.640
we could actually make some
progress trying to understand

00:38:17.640 --> 00:38:19.710
how they speak to each other.

00:38:19.710 --> 00:38:24.410
So in terms of your industry
and what you're dealing with,

00:38:24.410 --> 00:38:25.900
what would be your
fictional ideal

00:38:25.900 --> 00:38:28.130
big data set that currently
you can't collect or is

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:30.960
too expensive to collect
and you would love to play,

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:35.101
be it a game or
health or similar?

00:38:35.101 --> 00:38:36.850
ADAM KUCHARSKI: So in
terms of my day job,

00:38:36.850 --> 00:38:40.712
I think one of the big questions
that we don't know-- generally,

00:38:40.712 --> 00:38:42.420
we focus on things we
can measure easily.

00:38:42.420 --> 00:38:44.642
You know, a disease
case is been diagnosed.

00:38:44.642 --> 00:38:45.350
That's the thing.

00:38:45.350 --> 00:38:47.984
If we for Ebola put
in a treatment center,

00:38:47.984 --> 00:38:49.400
that's something
you can quantify.

00:38:49.400 --> 00:38:50.899
I think the thing
that's really hard

00:38:50.899 --> 00:38:52.519
to measure is
behavior and attitude

00:38:52.519 --> 00:38:54.060
and how they change
during outbreaks.

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:57.400
And I think they change a
lot, particularly for Ebola.

00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:00.130
We see it in some areas,
the epidemic would tail off.

00:39:00.130 --> 00:39:04.670
And anything you could shove in
a model would not explain that.

00:39:04.670 --> 00:39:07.286
There was clearly some
feedback process happening,

00:39:07.286 --> 00:39:09.660
and people were seeing what
was going around and changing

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:12.110
their behavior accordingly,
and I think just in reaction

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:14.310
to a lot of other
of these outbreaks.

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:16.820
And that's something
that's quite hard to--

00:39:16.820 --> 00:39:18.960
I think often we try to
measure stuff as proxies.

00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:20.990
You can do surveys of
people and their behavior.

00:39:20.990 --> 00:39:22.840
But if I ask you what
you're doing today

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:24.970
and there's a huge
outbreak next year,

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:26.690
can't guarantee you're going
to behave in the same way.

00:39:26.690 --> 00:39:28.080
And I think that's
something that

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:31.720
would be really interesting
to try and understand actually

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:34.420
what people really do versus
maybe what they say they do

00:39:34.420 --> 00:39:37.480
or what they think they do
and how that has an effect,

00:39:37.480 --> 00:39:39.740
because I think that's a
big gap in our understanding

00:39:39.740 --> 00:39:41.081
of outbreaks certainly.

00:39:41.081 --> 00:39:42.580
