rather than, if I played
this game an infinite number

00:40:59.940 --> 00:41:03.390
of times, I might make a
profit, think of it of,

00:41:03.390 --> 00:41:04.810
how much is this worth to me?

00:41:04.810 --> 00:41:06.920
How big a bankroll do
I need to make it worth

00:41:06.920 --> 00:41:07.940
buying a 2-pound ticket.

00:41:07.940 --> 00:41:10.640
And actually, in that case,
with these kind of lottery

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:12.334
rollovers, buying
a single ticket

00:41:12.334 --> 00:41:14.500
is only worth it if you're
a billionaire, basically,

00:41:14.500 --> 00:41:17.100
from a utility point of view,
which is not a great message.

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:19.350
But I think there was a lot
of focus on people saying,

00:41:19.350 --> 00:41:20.390
well, you know,
it's expected value.

00:41:20.390 --> 00:41:21.473
It's a great week to play.

00:41:21.473 --> 00:41:24.400
But the nuance of actually how
do you make those decisions,

00:41:24.400 --> 00:41:27.100
I think, was a quite interesting
thing to think about.

00:41:27.100 --> 00:41:30.310
MALE SPEAKER: You're talking
about obviously the strategies

00:41:30.310 --> 00:41:32.450
for playing games
and stuff but also

00:41:32.450 --> 00:41:36.700
in relationship to banking,
investments, and stuff.

00:41:36.700 --> 00:41:40.477
Obviously, that's an area where
different people are competing

00:41:40.477 --> 00:41:41.560
with different strategies.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:44.180
But as soon as one strategy
starts to take hold,

00:41:44.180 --> 00:41:46.000
then that changes the
environment in which

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:47.166
the strategies are behaving.

00:41:47.166 --> 00:41:50.430
So are there any
interesting things

00:41:50.430 --> 00:41:53.447
happening in trying to predict
not only when you introduce

00:41:53.447 --> 00:41:55.030
a strategy and how
it will do, but how

00:41:55.030 --> 00:41:56.830
it will change the environment?

00:41:56.830 --> 00:41:57.730
ADAM KUCHARSKI: Yeah,
that's a very good point.

00:41:57.730 --> 00:42:00.146
And that's one thing that
people are starting to work more

00:42:00.146 --> 00:42:01.835
actively actually
is-- I think there's

00:42:01.835 --> 00:42:04.180
a lot of focus on finance from
an individual point of view.

00:42:04.180 --> 00:42:05.650
You've got a single
investor, a single strategy.

00:42:05.650 --> 00:42:07.441
But of course, it's
basically an ecosystem.

00:42:07.441 --> 00:42:10.442
And a few people compare it
to an evolutionary dynamic,

00:42:10.442 --> 00:42:12.150
that if you come up
with a good strategy,

00:42:12.150 --> 00:42:13.100
other people adopt it.

00:42:13.100 --> 00:42:15.021
And then it becomes
less successful,

00:42:15.021 --> 00:42:17.020
and then you have to kind
of evolve what you do.

00:42:17.020 --> 00:42:21.120
And they're saying the
bigger the advantage,

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:24.299
the quicker it's going to decay
in terms of effectiveness,

00:42:24.299 --> 00:42:26.090
because it'll be easier
for people to spot.

00:42:26.090 --> 00:42:29.480
And I think for these
high-speed things in particular,

00:42:29.480 --> 00:42:32.890
that time scale is quite
short, because if you speed up

00:42:32.890 --> 00:42:35.830
what you're doing, you have such
a big edge over other people

00:42:35.830 --> 00:42:38.170
that there's a big incentive
for them to come in.

00:42:38.170 --> 00:42:41.190
And in one case, for
example, the people

00:42:41.190 --> 00:42:42.794
are building a
hardwire from-- I don't

00:42:42.794 --> 00:42:44.670
know if you heard about this--
from London to New York,

00:42:44.670 --> 00:42:47.100
underneath the flight path,
because it would give them

00:42:47.100 --> 00:42:50.730
a fraction of a second quicker
information on the market.

00:42:50.730 --> 00:42:55.110
And building that cable
is sufficiently valuable

00:42:55.110 --> 00:42:56.210
to actually get that edge.

00:42:56.210 --> 00:42:57.880
So I think in
particular, as the speed

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:00.310
increases, that evolutionary
process is increasing a lot.

00:43:00.310 --> 00:43:02.570
And I think there's a
lot we don't understand.

00:43:02.570 --> 00:43:03.840
I mean, you can take
some of the basic ideas

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:06.340
from ecology, about what happens
when you put lots of people

00:43:06.340 --> 00:43:06.870
together.

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:09.860
And one of the classical results
actually from chaos theory

00:43:09.860 --> 00:43:11.856
in the '70s was, if
you have something

00:43:11.856 --> 00:43:13.230
following simple
rules, it can do

00:43:13.230 --> 00:43:14.522
very weird, complicated things.

00:43:14.522 --> 00:43:16.855
I think we're seeing similar
things in finance, that you

00:43:16.855 --> 00:43:19.280
have a load of algorithms
written with 10 lines of code

00:43:19.280 --> 00:43:21.113
sitting together, and
they don't necessarily

00:43:21.113 --> 00:43:22.420
do what you think they'd do.

00:43:22.420 --> 00:43:25.024
So I think that's quite an
interesting, important field,

00:43:25.024 --> 00:43:26.690
but one that hasn't
been fully explored.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:29.560
So it'll be nice to see
what happens in the future.

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:32.370
AUDIENCE: Going back a bit
to the disease outbreaks,

00:43:32.370 --> 00:43:34.960
you mentioned that that data
is sometimes not complete.

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:37.830
So I was wondering, where do
you usually get that data?

00:43:37.830 --> 00:43:39.380
And once you get
the results, how

00:43:39.380 --> 00:43:41.100
does that data turn into action?

00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:43.620
Do you just give it
back to the government?

00:43:43.620 --> 00:43:45.299
How does that work?

00:43:45.299 --> 00:43:47.590
ADAM KUCHARSKI: So it varies
depending on the outbreak.

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:50.620
I mean, so with Ebola
and these kind of things,

00:43:50.620 --> 00:43:52.600
ideally you have
data on the cases

00:43:52.600 --> 00:43:56.580
as they're being
collected at the time.

00:43:56.580 --> 00:43:59.160
We're working directly with
agencies as well as WHO.

00:43:59.160 --> 00:44:01.159
You had Medecins Sans
Frontieres, and these kind

00:44:01.159 --> 00:44:04.710
of groups and actually kind
of converting the data back

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:07.510
into a potential
forecast for them.

00:44:07.510 --> 00:44:09.060
So I think with
all these things,

00:44:09.060 --> 00:44:11.040
it kind of works best if
you work with the people who

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:13.581
created the data, because they
understand how it's collected,

00:44:13.581 --> 00:44:15.380
and it's potentially useful.

00:44:15.380 --> 00:44:16.796
But I think one
of the things that

00:44:16.796 --> 00:44:19.500
was surprising with Ebola, for
example, is that in many cases,

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:21.164
people collecting
data in one district

00:44:21.164 --> 00:44:23.330
didn't actually have the
data for the next district.

00:44:23.330 --> 00:44:25.460
So we had a situation
where we were synthesizing

00:44:25.460 --> 00:44:27.350
it and visualizing it
and giving it back,

00:44:27.350 --> 00:44:29.790
so they kind of knew what
the border picture was.

00:44:29.790 --> 00:44:32.769
And it's quite a
basic data analysis,

00:44:32.769 --> 00:44:35.310
because it's essentially just
cleaning it and visualizing it.

00:44:35.310 --> 00:44:37.280
But I think in some of
these situations, that's

00:44:37.280 --> 00:44:38.780
almost the most important
thing-- that you

00:44:38.780 --> 00:44:40.570
can do fancy modeling
in the long term.

00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:43.390
But really the fundamental
thing on the day

00:44:43.390 --> 00:44:44.910
is, what's the situation?

00:44:44.910 --> 00:44:47.291
Is this the kind of idea of
nowcasting for a disease?

00:44:47.291 --> 00:44:48.790
You're always looking
into the past,

00:44:48.790 --> 00:44:50.850
because you have
these delays in terms

00:44:50.850 --> 00:44:54.320
of how the data come
through and under-reporting

00:44:54.320 --> 00:44:55.320
and those sort of stuff.

00:44:55.320 --> 00:44:57.750
So the data that comes
in today might actually

00:44:57.750 --> 00:44:59.690
be representing what
happened a few weeks ago.

00:44:59.690 --> 00:45:01.632
So even just making
those adjustments

00:45:01.632 --> 00:45:03.590
and giving them back to
the people in the field

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:06.340
can be quite a useful exercise.

00:45:06.340 --> 00:45:10.064
AUDIENCE: You've discussed how
in chess, Go, poker, roulette--

00:45:10.064 --> 00:45:11.480
these kind of
games-- there's been

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:14.780
sound kind of breakthrough
in which someone could

00:45:14.780 --> 00:45:17.770
be pretty much all the others.

00:45:17.770 --> 00:45:21.090
What kind of game do you see
next, where this could happen,

00:45:21.090 --> 00:45:24.000
where somebody could
develop a new strategy

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:28.020
or get more data than anyone
else and beat the system?

00:45:28.020 --> 00:45:30.360
ADAM KUCHARSKI: So which
game might fall next?

00:45:30.360 --> 00:45:34.054
I think poker,
certainly no limits.

00:45:34.054 --> 00:45:35.220
We're kind of at that point.

00:45:35.220 --> 00:45:37.630
So there's a
tournament last year,

00:45:37.630 --> 00:45:39.350
where bots kind
of played humans.

00:45:39.350 --> 00:45:41.266
And they played a vast
amount number of hands.

00:45:41.266 --> 00:45:43.600
The humans came out with a
very slightly smaller pot

00:45:43.600 --> 00:45:44.280
on average.

00:45:44.280 --> 00:45:45.970
So naturally the
researcher said that

00:45:45.970 --> 00:45:48.140
wasn't statistically
significant and the human

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:49.534
said that they had won.

00:45:49.534 --> 00:45:50.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:51.349 --> 00:45:53.140
So I think we're reaching
that point where,

00:45:53.140 --> 00:45:56.390
if you talk to professionals,
these games are still safe.

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:58.770
If you talk to the guys
working the algorithms,

00:45:58.770 --> 00:45:59.990
it's only a matter of time.

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:01.900
And I think it's
particularly interesting we

00:46:01.900 --> 00:46:05.540
have these strong feelings about
games that are seen as an art.

00:46:05.540 --> 00:46:07.220
So a lot of these
poker kind of games

00:46:07.220 --> 00:46:11.250
are scene as very
experienced players

00:46:11.250 --> 00:46:14.150
with intuition and instinct.

00:46:14.150 --> 00:46:15.380
I think that's their realm.

00:46:15.380 --> 00:46:17.879
So it's quite interesting as
computers start to come into it

00:46:17.879 --> 00:46:19.630
and challenge those notions.

00:46:19.630 --> 00:46:21.796
So yeah, I think that's
going to be the one to watch

00:46:21.796 --> 00:46:23.690
in the next couple years.

